sh <i>thorp(e)</i> ‘village, hamlet, farmstead’ (Old Norse, Old English <i>thorp</i> ‘secondary settlement’). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived in such a settlement, or habitational, for someone from any of several places called Thorp(e), which are most frequent in Yorkshire, the Midlands, and East Anglia. Compare   Throop  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Trupp","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Hermann, Reinhold.","English (Herefordshire and Monmouthshire): variant of   Thorpe  , or from a place so named, such as Thrupp (Berkshire, Gloucestershire, Oxfordshire), Thrupe (Somerset), Throop (Dorset, Hampshire, Somerset), and Throope (Wiltshire).","Altered form of German   Trapp  ."]},{"name":"Throop","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>throp</i> ‘village, hamlet, farmstead’ (Old Norse, Old English <i>throp</i> ‘secondary settlement’). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived in such a settlement, or habitational, for someone from Throop in Hampshire, Throope in Wiltshire, Thrup in Oxfordshire, or any of the places called Thrupp in Berkshire, Gloucestershire, and Northamptonshire. Compare   Thorpe  ."]},{"name":"Tharpe","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Thorpe  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Thorp","meanings":["English (mainly Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Thorpe  .","Scandinavian: variant of   Torp  ."]},{"name":"Troup","meanings":["Scottish (eastern): habitational name from a place in the parish of Gamrie, near Banff. The placename is unexplained, perhaps a Pictish cognate of Welsh <i>trwp</i> ‘vessel, dish, basin’.","Possibly also English, a metathesized form of   Thorpe  ."]},{"name":"Tharp","meanings":["English: variant of   Thorpe  ."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes Thorpe was born in 1380, in Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with Sir William De Rookewood."},"et":{"1380–":"1380–Surnud","1371–1422":"1371–1422","1393–Male":"1393–Surnud","1380–Female":"1380–Surnud","1422":"1422","1393":"1393","1371":"1371","1380":"1380","Illington, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Illington, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1380–":"1380–Kuollut","1371–1422":"1371–1422","1393–Male":"1393–Kuollut","1380–Female":"1380–Kuollut","1422":"1422","1393":"1393","1371":"1371","1380":"1380","Illington, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Illington, Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1380–":"1380–Décédée","1371–1422":"1371–1422","1393–Male":"1393–Décédé","1380–Female":"1380–Décédée","1422":"1422","1393":"1393","1371":"1371","1380":"1380","Illington, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Illington, Norfolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Suffolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Agnes Thorpe est née en 1380, à Suffolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Sir William De Rookewood."},"de":{"1380–":"1380–Verstorben","1371–1422":"1371–1422","1393